          <div class="myths-grid">
            <div class="myths-item fade-in">
              <h3>Myth: Black holes are cosmic vacuum cleaners</h3>
              <p>Fact: Black holes do not actively suck in matter from their surroundings. Objects must come within the event horizon to be affected by the black hole's gravity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="myths-item fade-in">
              <h3>Myth: Black holes can destroy the universe</h3>
              <p>Fact: Black holes are not powerful enough to destroy the entire universe. They can only affect objects within their gravitational influence.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="myths-item fade-in">
              <h3>Myth: Black holes are always black</h3>
              <p>Fact: Black holes emit a faint glow known as Hawking radiation, which means they are not completely black.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="myths-item fade-in">
              <h3>Myth: Black holes are portals to other dimensions</h3>
              <p>Fact: There is no scientific evidence to support the idea that black holes are portals to other dimensions or parallel universes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="myths-item fade-in">
              <h3>Myth: Black holes can travel through space</h3>
              <p>Fact: Black holes do not move through space on their own. They remain stationary unless acted upon by external forces, such as the gravitational pull of other objects.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="myths-item fade-in">
              <h3>Myth: Black holes are infinitely dense</h3>
              <p>Fact: While black holes have extremely high density, they are not infinitely dense. The density of a black hole depends on its mass and size.</p>
